tickets, [375879,7,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr","b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","end-to-end File Encryption [XL]",2,"Goal: end-to-end data confidentiality and authenticity.  \n\nViewing FileSender as a file transport channel, encryption is  preferably done end-to-end, where all data leaves the sender's client encrypted and gets decrypted on the receivers client.  The server should never see plaintext data.  If this is not viable, server-side encryption can be considered to improve \"at rest\" protection.  Note that the effects are different though:\n\n* Client-side: data is *never* plain text on the server: a server hack would have no influence (provided the javascript served to users isn't changed ;)\n\n* Server-side: data is plain-text on the server until encrypted *after* upload, and plaintext after decryption before download\n\n\nImportant constraints:\n-encryption functionality must be possible without provisioning stuff to the user.  The user should be able to use it without installing anything.  This implies it ought to be done using plain javascript.\n-encryption functionality must not imply additional server-side infrastructural requirements to f.ex. get a key to a user (sms gateway).  This is nice added functionality, but we must maintain a filesender install that is fully functional with least possible server-side complications\n-the encryption key must not be transferred using the same channel as the download link is transferred\n\nIt is perfectly acceptable to have this \"power funcionality\" only work in HTml5 fileAPI supporting browsers\n\nNote that as soon as we have this working, we also need to investigate signed javascript: in the scenario where a FileSender server is hacked, end-users need to be able to rely on the integrity of the javascript code used for encryption.  It looks like this ought to be possible: http://answers.uchicago.edu/page.php?id=19495","2009-05-20T07:33:27.000+00:00","2016-02-26T14:04:04.000+00:00",114623,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2016-02-26T14:04:04.000+00:00",0.0,0,7.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2016-02-26T14:04:04.000+00:00",null]
