tickets, [1111605,138,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Email address with 1 character refused with \"Please select file to upload\" error",3,"When using an email address as \"x@uninett.no\" the Flash UI app comes up with an error like \"please select a file for upload\".  This bug has two issues associated with it:\n\n1. An email address with 1 character before the @ is a perfectly valid address that is in use with many a system administrator (exactly the type of people I talk with to get them to introduce our service in their institution ;)\n\n2. The error is totally wrong!  \n\nI know that there are issues with email address handling but at least the error should be appropriate ;)","2010-03-19T12:04:26.000+00:00","2011-09-21T18:44:20.000+00:00",345073,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2010-03-22T23:56:00.000+00:00",0.0,0,138.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1111649,139,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Multi-language email templates [L]",3,"With version 1.5 we have a multi-language UI.  The email templates are still one language.  This might be a problem we can not solve.  \n\nHow do you deal with a Norwegian user sending a file to a Brazilian user?  The Brazilian might not want to receive a Norwegian email.  A Norwegian email with \"english at the bottom\" might also not be desirable.  Letting people set the language of the recipients sounds cumbersome and would be unwieldy with multiple recipients.  \n\nThere is no widely deployed mechanism to let an email client pick a locale on behalf of the recipient.  \n\nSo this problem appears to be a thorny one: we know who the *sender* is, but have no clue about the receiver.  The user knows but shouldn't be bothered with questions about that and besides, allowing a user to set a certain attribute of a recipient stimulates the next desire: being able to store such information about recipients.  We currently store no permanent information whatsoever and that makes the service very easy to run, which is a characteristic we should think carefully about before giving it up.\n\n","2010-03-19T12:13:21.000+00:00","2012-02-07T17:18:05.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb",null,0.0,0,139.0,0,0,28660,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1111701,140,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Help button in Flash UI",3,"Feature: help button\n--------------------\nLike the about link, have a Help link in the UI.  This feature introduces a new configure switch.\n\n'Help_Link_Visible' true/false, triggering the visibility of the link.  The Help text itself will be included in the language file.\n\nThis feature will be implemented in the Beta-1.10.\n","2010-03-19T12:26:32.000+00:00","2015-11-11T10:46:19.000+00:00",345073,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2010-03-25T11:20:40.000+00:00",0.0,0,-16.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2015-11-11T10:46:19.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [1111733,141,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Configurable AuP checkbox in Flash UI",3,"I felt the need to have the possibility to force a user to accept an AuP.  From a user's perspective the nicest is to do that once and never again.  Easiest to implement at this point in time is to force a user to accept the AuP every time.\n\nWhat we'll implement for Beta-1.10 is:\n\nunderneath the 'file' button a checkbox with label \n\"I accept the terms and conditions of this service\", the checkbox next to it, \nand listbox with text of AuP next to that.  4/5 lines high.\n\nA big 'Send' button underneath that. Send button as big as 'Message' box is \nat the moment.\n\n\nMake it mandatory to tick the box before you can upload.  Check both \nclient side and server side.\n\nFurther discussion with Guido later today lead to the belief that this feature should be configurable.  As in: \n-a configurable switch 'AuP' = true/false\n\ncombined with\n\n-a configurable swith 'AuP_Default_Set'=true/false\n\n\nThe feature will be available in Beta-1.10:\n","2010-03-19T12:35:35.000+00:00","2015-11-11T10:46:19.000+00:00",345073,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2010-03-25T23:24:40.000+00:00",0.0,0,-17.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2015-11-11T10:46:19.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [1112395,142,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","limit file upload recipient to voucher creator [M]",3,"The voucher issuer can select an option by which the voucher receiver can only sent the file to voucher issuer, i.e. \"To:\"\n= e-mail address of voucher issuer.\n\nAn implementation question is whether this is a side-wide decision or a per-voucher-issuer decision.\n\n1. make it a side-wide decision.  A server admin can decide to switch this on, or off.  On means upload invitations can only be used to upload a file to the originator of the invitation.\nOff means uploads can be sent to anyone\n\n2. make it a possible choice for the originator of an invitation.  Allow them to tick this as an option when creating an upload invitation.  The option might be ticked by default, or not\n(another config option).\n\nIf you have a fairly constrained use case (for example to provide a \"dump your multi-GB error trace files here\" facility to customers of a machine) the first option would fit the bill.\n\nIf you'd like to make this the general default but would like to offer users the option to divert (for example: research collaboration of 4 people, of which one (A) has access to a\nfilesender instance, wanting to enable persons B and C to send a file directly) from the default, we'd need option (2) as well.\n\nImplementation ought to start with option (1), and then proceed with option (2).   Option (2) has UI consequences.","2010-03-19T15:32:39.000+00:00","2016-02-26T14:58:43.000+00:00",6605143,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","2016-02-26T14:33:02.000+00:00",0.0,0,-116.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2016-02-26T14:58:43.000+00:00",null]
