tickets, [1624261,232,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","gears upload tmpfile handling",3,"The gears upload uses the tmpfiles directory to store the uploaded chunks under the 'orignal filename'. When two separate users/sessions are uploading a file with the same filename the chunks are added to a single file in the tmpfiles directory. This leads a.o. to corrupt files and information leakage. Solution would be to use a unique (user-dependent?) identifier (either a subdir or prefix for the filename).\n\nHow to reproduce (at least on 0.1.13 and 0.1.14): \n\ntake two *different* files (reasonably large so that it takes a while to upload) and give them the same name (i.e. testfile.tst). Have two users (or 1 user and two separate browsers/machine) upload the file (one user/browser one of the two files, the other user/browser the other) at the same time. Compare the resulting files after upload (check size and md5sum).","2010-06-23T09:41:31.000+00:00","2014-10-21T22:19:49.000+00:00",345073,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","2010-09-20T22:50:05.000+00:00",0.0,0,232.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1628949,233,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Modify file deletion process",3,"Currently files are marked deleted and rendered inaccessible on expiry/deletion.  But the actual deletion is run on login of the next user.  This should be made more predictable.  probably through use of a time-based process: say a cron job that runs once every hour to delete what needs to be deleted.  Users want to know *when* their file is actually thrown away.\n\nCome to think of it: rather then deleting we might want to advise proper 'secure deletion' of a file to make sure no remnants remain.","2010-06-24T08:18:46.000+00:00","2010-11-08T10:51:23.000+00:00",114623,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","2010-11-08T10:51:23.000+00:00",0.0,0,233.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
