tickets, [1659885,242,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","move config.php from classes to a new config directory",3,"I think it is a good idea to move the config.php from classes to a separated config folder. This is more clear for the end user, but also separates logic to configuration.","2010-07-01T12:18:00.000+00:00","2011-01-29T11:54:12.000+00:00",345073,null,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2010-08-02T11:48:05.000+00:00",0.0,0,242.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1659921,243,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Remove hostname from config.php or define it once",3,"\nCurrently you need to define the filesender installation urls at multiple locations in the config.php file:\n\n\t$config['site_url'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/'; // URL to Filesender\n\t$config['site_simplesamlurl'] = 'http://siteurl/simplesamlphp/';\n\t$config['site_downloadurl'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/files/';\n\t$config['site_logouturl'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/logout.php';\n\nI'm not sure why the hostname is required, since filesender could also work with relative links/redirects. The only usecase I could think of is when for example the files are hosted on a different machine/virtualhost. Anyway, it is a good idea to specify the hostname only once, this is less typing and less error prone. I'm not sure what is 'cloudstor' also, I think that is a test machine something that slipped into the release.\n","2010-07-01T12:24:32.000+00:00","2011-01-29T11:54:12.000+00:00",345073,null,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2010-08-25T23:57:09.000+00:00",0.0,0,243.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1660065,244,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Restructure SVN tree to support branches and tags",3,"At the moment there are no subfolders for trunk, tags and branches. This can become quite handy when managing multiple releases. I propose a restructure of the SVN tree where the current root is relocated to a 'trunk' subfolder, and every release is is copied into a 'branch'. From where a release is prepared.","2010-07-01T12:51:00.000+00:00","2011-01-29T11:54:12.000+00:00",345073,null,"b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2010-08-05T12:58:34.000+00:00",0.0,0,244.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1675255,245,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Investigate command line Flash compilation to enable automatic nightly builds",3,"Gijs wants to implement automatic nightly builds.  For that the Flash app needs to be able to be automatically compiled from the command line.  Chris will look with Gijs whether and how this can be done.","2010-07-05T12:10:14.000+00:00","2014-10-21T22:19:50.000+00:00",213323,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2010-07-15T10:17:33.000+00:00",0.0,0,245.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1676075,246,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Detailed transaction logging facility per user",3,"At the moment when something goes wrong with a file upload we have insufficient information to figure out where in the client or in the server the problem might be.  It's difficult to ask the person with the problem to tell us what went wrong where, reproduce it etc.  Better it would be to have proper logging.  \n\nTo solve this we can implement client-side step-by-step logging that sends a log line to the server for every 'processing step' the client takes.  Server side it would result in one logfile per user.  Preferably with the username in the filename to make debugging for the server admin easy.  The logging would be switched on/off from the server side.  Server side a filter based on ePTID would select for which users logging would be maintained.  That way you wouldn't get too much of logging on a busy server.  \n\nThe logging would have to log both the client side steps and the server side steps for that particular user in 1 integrated logfile.\n\nIf we have this in the code then even though sometimes things wouldn't work, we at least have a solid handle on where something went wrong.   \n\n\n\n\n\n\nDifferent combinations of operating system (version) - browser (version)  - flash version have different results and it's difficult to pinpoint exactly what piece of code was responsible for stuff going wrong.  \n\nTo solve this functionality needs to be imp","2010-07-05T13:49:31.000+00:00","2011-01-29T12:01:56.000+00:00",345073,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","2010-10-14T12:35:56.000+00:00",0.0,0,246.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [1679437,247,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Extra field in download page indicating download progress in actual bytes",3,"I'm currently using an untuned Windows machine to download a 40GB file from the Australian filesender installation.  It took so long for the progress bar to move to 1% that I had to check whether it was actually doing something ;)\n\nI'm thinking: an extra field in the download page that tells a user how many bytes have actually been transferred, and how many are still to go, that might help.\n\nIf you look at how FireFox implements this in their current download progress thingie when I'm downloading a Fedora DVD image:\n\n-it says '2% of 1 file - Downloads\"\n-FileName \n-status (... or Paused)\n-103 MB of 3.4 GB (9.0 MB/sec)\n-x minutes remaining\n\nThat looks pretty good to me.  Note: if we change to HTML5, maybe we get this free of charge by leveraging built in browser functionality?\n\n","2010-07-06T11:28:29.000+00:00","2010-11-08T10:52:29.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","2010-11-08T10:52:29.000+00:00",0.0,0,247.0,0,0,342706,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
