tickets, [3365012,382,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Screen confirmation prompts when sending to more than one recipient displaying multiple times",3,"The \"Your file has been uploaded and email sent\" text, \"Email sent\" button (resend email / adding recipients) and \"Voucher sent\" button are all coming up twice when there is more than one recipient (maybe also when downloading a file but as there is only one window there, that can't be determined and wouldn't matter anyway). Note that, at least in the case of the buttons, these two on-screen notifications are *not sequential*, rather they are displayed one behind the other *at the same time* - the grey semi-transparent background becomes lighter after one clicks on the button the first time, to reveal the second greay background and send button behind. Spotted by Xander on apps3, which he confirmed on a pristine 1.0 instance. Also confirmed and further details determined by Wendy on AARNet's current (patched) variant of 1.0.","2011-03-14T01:34:43.000+00:00","2013-09-10T12:35:48.000+00:00",345073,null,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2013-09-10T12:35:48.000+00:00",0.0,0,382.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2013-09-10T12:35:48.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [3365022,383,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Space infront of second email address and associated misalignment in My Files table",3,"In the My Files table, the second email entry in the \"To\" Field ends up seemingly aligned with the bottom of the row and gets truncated rather than wrapping - when expanding the column, a space infront of the address becomes evident and the address becomes aligned with the top of the row, so this would not appear to be due to an alignment setting. Wendy has confirmed this on apps3 and AARNet's current (patched) variant of 1.0. Xander has also confirmed on 1.0 and trunk.","2011-03-14T01:39:57.000+00:00","2011-05-02T17:57:11.000+00:00",345073,null,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2011-05-02T17:57:11.000+00:00",0.0,0,383.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3428489,384,"bcgVDMwiSr3AYAab7jnrAJ","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","mail bounce handling: decision time",2,"by default, the way filesender sends emails (impersonating the sending user) is not SPF-compliant. Two alternative schemes have been implemented in/around filesender to mitigate the issue.\n\n- one provides SPF compliance using an SRS scheme implemented through EXIM4 and a separate SRS daemon, described here: http://www.assembla.com/wiki/show/file_sender/Configuring_SRS_with_Exim_%28Debian_and_Ubuntu%29\n\n- another reverts to filesender sending emails as itself (omitting the impersonation), and making use of additional code to tag outgoing emails and parse their headers should they bounce, thus enabling filesender to forward any bounces to the sending user. This method is described here: http://www.assembla.com/wiki/show/file_sender/Mail_Bounce_Handling\n\nBoth procedures have been tested and are proven to work; I believe it's time to choose one as the default developmental route.","2011-03-22T13:13:36.000+00:00","2015-12-03T11:13:55.000+00:00",345073,null,"bcgVDMwiSr3AYAab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA,bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","2011-05-17T21:24:20.000+00:00",0.0,0,-82.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2015-12-03T11:13:55.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [3520379,385,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Quota support [M]",3,"The goal of quota support is to be able to restrict how many resources a user uses.\n\nOption 1: cumulative upload-size limit: a maximum to the total size of active files a user has on a FileSender install \nOption 2: time-relative upload-size limit per user: a user can only upload a certain amount of data in a certain time frame\nOption 3: max. number of uploads in a certain time period\n\nOption (3) sounds illogical: the resource consumed is the amount of disk, not the amount of network sockets.  Option (1) might be the most logical one as it offers a user some form of control: if they go over their quota, they can encourage the downloader to download quickly so they get free upload slots again.\n\nIt ought to be a system-wide setting, one size fits all.  User-specific settings we have no way to maintain, so those need to come out of the authentication source.","2011-04-01T10:15:52.000+00:00","2013-03-19T20:59:08.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,385.0,0,0,238024,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2013-03-19T20:47:54.000+00:00",null]
