tickets, [3574399,389,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Gears fileSize limits can be circumvented",3,"n upload_gears.mxml there are a few checks on filesize (and other stuff\nthat's not allowed):\n\n1) fileSize = 0\n2) os - Mac and fileSize > 2G\n3) fileSize > max_gears_upload_size\n\nIn all these cases the user gets the pop up just after selecting the fie\n(good) *but* in all these cases the selected file is put in the UI and\nthe SEND button appears. So even after the warning (too large) a user\nstill can upload the 'illegal' file by pressing SEND.\n\nThe fun part is that this is only when using gears. In the\nupload_std.mxml (flash upload) everything is OK, the user gets the popup\nwarning, the file-part in the UI is cleared and there is *NO* SEND\nbutton to press.\n\nThere is some code in upload_gears.mxml that looks like it should\nprevent the SEND button appearing after a warning but that doesn't seem\nto do the job.","2011-04-08T06:48:01.000+00:00","2011-09-22T05:06:09.000+00:00",345073,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2011-05-13T10:33:47.000+00:00",0.0,0,389.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3574493,390,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Mac 2GB limit message can appear when selecting zero sized file",3,"If I have previously selected a 2 GB file, the message \"Mac using gears cannot upload a file larger than 2 GB (Error # 032)\" is repeated if I subsequently select a zero sized file, then when I click on OK the proper message is revealed \"Cannot upload a file of 0 bytes. Please select another file.\" This was with Gears, on Mac OSX 10.6.7, FF 3.6.16, Flash 10.2.152.33.","2011-04-08T07:05:03.000+00:00","2011-05-13T10:35:56.000+00:00",345073,null,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2011-05-13T10:35:56.000+00:00",0.0,0,390.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3574627,391,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Logout warning about still existing 'IdP sessions'",3,"The SURFnet Office IdP replaces the normal SP logout page with a strong security advice when logging out of a service like FileSender. This should warn users that logging out of one specific service doesn't terminate other sessions one might have to other services and also doesn't clear the 'main' session with the identity provider of the user. This makes it possible to login again to FileSender without being asked for credentials. We might want to add a warning about this to the FileSender logout page.\n\nThe (a bit technical) text from the SURFet IdP as example:\n-------------\nDue to the nature of this centralized authentication infrastructure and the type of sessions that you have running, it not possible to terminate all of your sessions with each Service Provider with 100% certainty. There is only one option for guaranteed secure logout:\n\nShutdown your browser when you want to end your running sessions in a secure way!\n\nApologies for the inconvenience: this is a strong security advice.\n-------------\n\nSuggestion from Wendy: \"Your logout from FileSender is complete. To ensure you have also been logged out from  your institutional identity provider, please quit your browser.\"\n\nPossible bears on the road:\n- does this cover all cases ? (is every logon to FileSender 'federative'? How about a local u/p database setup?\n","2011-04-08T07:26:29.000+00:00","2011-04-08T07:31:06.000+00:00",114011,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,391.0,0,0,28660,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3718100,392,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Allow uploader to disable download receipt email to file *recipient*",3,"The concrete use case that triggered this is when someone sends a large file to a mailing list.  The receipt email \"person X has downloaded file Y\" is sent *to* the uploader with a Cc: to the *downloader/recipient*.  If the recipient is an email list, the Cc: will go to the email list for every download.  If you distribute a file to a list with several 100 people, that is a bit .. annoying.\n\nThe difficulty here is to cater for use cases like this without complicating the user interface.  A solution might be to have different \"filesender user views\" depending on which \"persona\" you are.  Using personas is a common technique in user interaction design.  You define a limited number of persons with certain characteristics as the people you imagine will use the software and cater to their needs.  \n\nFor FileSender this might be: a first time user, someone who uses the functionality \"as is\" and someone who considers him/herself as a \"power user\" and wants to be able to tweak more of the experience.  The first time user would for example have access to a more \"guided\" approach, a \"as is\" user knows how to use FileSender but needs no advanced functionality nor does he want to be bothered with the \"guided use\".   The power user would have the option to switch stuff on and off.\n\nThis would lead to 3 views on the functionality.  \n\nI am tempted to think we need to go that way, as we also need to figure out how to incorporate for example time stamping in the UI.\n\nThis requires more thought and more speccing, but at least it is a ticket now....\n","2011-04-27T10:52:19.000+00:00","2011-04-27T10:52:19.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,392.0,0,0,28660,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3733866,393,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","IE8 JavaScript error",3,"When using IE8 a Gears upload shows an 'Error on page' warning icon. Uploads are fine though.\n\n\"Webpage error details\n\nUser Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; Trident/4.0; SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; InfoPath.2)\nTimestamp: Thu, 28 Apr 2011 12:11:39 UTC\n\n\nMessage: Request is not loading or done.\nLine: 221\nChar: 3\nCode: 0\nURI: https://filesender.belnet.be/filesender/js/fs_gears.js\n\"\nReported by a Belnet test user and confirmed on a W7/IE8 install at SURFnet","2011-04-28T18:25:23.000+00:00","2013-09-10T12:38:13.000+00:00",345073,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA,dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2013-09-10T12:38:13.000+00:00",0.0,0,393.0,0,0,3316353,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2013-09-10T12:38:13.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [3744160,394,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","File too large, use Gears warnings inconsistent",3,"There are two points where the user gets a 'File too large, use Gears' warning using Flash only uploads. The actual messages are not the same. Also the message needs some cleanup (punctuation and clarification about the max size reported). Spotted by Wendy.\n\n","2011-04-29T20:00:39.000+00:00","2011-05-02T17:56:45.000+00:00",345073,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2011-05-02T17:56:45.000+00:00",0.0,0,394.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
