tickets, [3753990,397,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Inconsistent wrapping of Subject in My Files list",4,"Sometimes (seems to be depending on the first entry in the My Files list) longer subjects are not wrapped. If the Subject column isn't wide enough, not all the text might be displayed until the user widens the column.","2011-05-02T14:43:59.000+00:00","2011-05-13T10:36:53.000+00:00",345073,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2011-05-13T10:36:53.000+00:00",0.0,0,397.0,0,0,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3782492,398,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Enable expiry time extension",3,"Yesterday I presented CloudStor to about 40 faculty-IT support at NTNU, Trondheim Uni.  One of them came with the question whether it was possible, in MyFiles, to extend the expiry time of a file.  Say you sent a file to someone, that someone turned out to be on holiday, then you might want to extend the expiry time.\n\nThoughts: treat this in the way libraries do?  Allow for one (or more, such to be configurable) extension of the expiry date, presumably using a button \"extend file availability period\".  Easiest would be if you would have a standard \"file availability extension\" period.  That would be server-configurable as well, and presumably one week would be a good default.  However, you can see coming that people would want to just pick a particular date: \"I *know* the person will be back on that and that date, so that date + 1 week is good.\"\n\nThis then implies both a button \"extend\" which does a standard extension plus a calendar which allows a user to set a more specific date.  The date box would need to be there anyway to show when the file is about to expire.  Having said that, there still ought to be a max expire, also on \"extension of availability\".  By far the easiest way to get started with this appears to be a simple button \"extend availability\" that simply extends availability with a configurable standard amount of time/days and not let the user pick something.\n\n","2011-05-05T07:38:55.000+00:00","2011-05-05T07:38:55.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,398.0,0,0,28660,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [3922793,399,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Multiple User Interface views, guided use vs. normal use",3,"Some users have \"computer fear\".  So while the FileSender UI is very self-explaining, some users need a little bit of assistance in first time use to allow them to overcome \"first use fear\".  \n\nWhat I imagine is that a first time user can have some \"first use assistance\" in the form of for example a little youtube video showing them how FileSender works (in their own language), and possibly a big help button.  Something like that.  \n\nBut this is UI clutter for those people who know quite well how to use it.  So hence this ticket: I would like to make it possible that a first time user gets a slightly different UI experience then a second time user.  This mechanism can be generalised to offer different groups different \"help\".\n","2011-05-18T08:15:00.000+00:00","2011-05-18T08:15:00.000+00:00",114011,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,399.0,0,0,28660,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
