tickets, [17115323,677,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Restructure naming of language files",3,"Current naming scheme of the language files deviates from Best Current Practices (as defined by BCP 47 and related ICU/ISO guidelines). Main deviation being the use of lower/upper case of language and country tags. To prevent confusion we should go to the following filename naming scheme:\n\n<language>_<COUNTRY>\n\n<language> is the shortest two/three letter ISO 639 language code in lowercase\n<COUNTRY> (or better perhaps <REGION>) is the ISO 3166-1 country/region/territory code in UPPERcase\n\nUse of \"_\" (underscore) in filenames follows the convention for defining 'locales' on modern Linux/Unix systems (and defined/allowd by the related Unicode/ICU definitions, see [[url:http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr35/#Unicode_Language_and_Locale_Identifiers|http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr35/#Unicode_Language_and_Locale_Identifiers]] )\n\nNote that browser tags for language preference use the \"-\" hyphen (as defined in BCP 47)\n\nChanging this in beta2 has two advantages:\n1) use of well used standard for naming locales (for filenames).\n2) no mix-up with 'old-style' language definitions in ./config (see related ticket #657)\n\nRe 2) Since we decided to move the distribution provided './config' language definitions to the main files in ./language', left-overs in '/.config' should not be used anymore unless they cotain local modifications. A side effect of renaming all language files now will be that the 'left-overs' in './config' won't be used anymore so the actual (and possibly changed) definitions in the './language' dir will always be used. pre-beta2 users can be directed to move local customisations (and only those) to a file according to the 'new' scheme.\n\n","2012-03-19T09:28:57.000+00:00","2012-08-30T16:04:56.000+00:00",394418,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2012-04-25T10:32:54.000+00:00",0.0,0,677.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [17266123,678,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb","dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Guest invite button syntax",3,"Suggest changing \"Guest invite\" button to \"Invite Guest\", which is more grammatically correct (an alternative is \"Guest Invitation\", but that is too long for a button) and also the capitalisation of both words would be in keeping with other link buttons across the top of the page.\n","2012-03-20T05:42:26.000+00:00","2012-03-21T11:16:05.000+00:00",394418,null,"aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA,dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2012-03-21T11:16:05.000+00:00",0.0,0,678.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [17897633,679,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Shred files to completey remove them when deleted ",3,"Submitted by Thijs Kinkhorst\n\nWithin our organisation there was the desire that files get not simply unlinked when they are expired but are wiped from disk by overwriting them with random data. This tries to combat the effect of filesender's filestore becoming a goldmine of assorted documents that would be easy to recover - somewhat like the infamous printer hard drives.\n\nAttached patch implements this. The wiping happens at night, so I think usually it will not matter much that it takes a little bit longer than unlinking. I did add a configurable option for it, for sites that don't want this functionality; the default is set to true now because I reasoned that it normally doesn't hurt, and there will probably only be a few sites for which it's necessary to turn it off. Still, I can imagine that you want to pick another default for this.\n\nIt makes use of GNU coreutils shred, which I think can safely be assumed to be available given the \"Linux\" requirement of filesender.\n","2012-03-29T06:33:21.000+00:00","2017-05-15T21:00:13.000+00:00",394418,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2012-07-20T08:14:33.000+00:00",0.0,0,-33.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2014-06-19T11:43:09.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [17897663,680,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Duplicate version numbers",3,"2xversion.patch: the filesender version number is displayed twice: both at the top-right and bottom of the page; the second one is not influenced by the 'versionNumber' setting from config.php, so I've removed that one altogether.\n\nSubmitted by Thijs Kinkhorst","2012-03-29T06:34:25.000+00:00","2017-05-15T20:53:34.000+00:00",null,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2012-10-13T21:36:18.000+00:00",0.0,0,680.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,"2012-10-13T21:36:18.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [17897753,681,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Display array in log correctly",3,"Note the repeated occurrence of 'Array' instead of the value in log file. With this patch, the multivalued attribute values are separated by a pipe, like this:\n\nSubmitted b y Thijs Kinkhorst","2012-03-29T06:35:40.000+00:00","2017-05-15T20:53:48.000+00:00",394418,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA","2012-04-11T14:27:02.000+00:00",0.0,0,681.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [17909113,682,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Aurora FF 13+ changed blob.mozslice back to blob.slice",3,"I was checking the Aurora build of Firefox to see if ff 13+ still breaks when uploading. It does :(.\nHowever after reading a bit about what changed I noted the following on http://hacks.mozilla.org/2012/03/firefox-aurora-13-is-out-spdy-on-by-default-and-a-list-of-other-improvements/\n\nUnprefix Blob.mozSlice: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=725289\nXander\n","2012-03-29T10:23:55.000+00:00","2012-08-30T16:06:22.000+00:00",394418,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA,bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","2012-05-09T20:53:58.000+00:00",0.0,0,682.0,0,1,447388,0,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
tickets, [17913063,683,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","possible performance improvement in www/fs_upload.php",3,"Not so much a bug, but something that is very related to 1.5\n\nChris and I were discussing upload speed for chunked (html5) upload and where there might be options for improvement.  I looked at http 1.1 keep_alive this week and didn't really see a difference in with or without.  Chris suggested to look at the bit where the chunks are actually written to the temp file.\nAround line 247 in www/fs_upload.php there's this code:\n\nwhile( $data = fread( $fd,  1000000  ) ) file_put_contents( $config[\"site_filestore\"].sanitizeFilename($tempFilename).checkFileSize($uploadfolder.$tempFilename).\"tmp\", $data ) or die(\"Error\");\n \nIt effectively \"chunks the chunk\".  It looked like changing that line to:\n\nfile_put_contents( $config[\"site_filestore\"].sanitizeFilename($tempFilename), $fd, FILE_APPEND ) or die(\"Error\");\n\nmade for an interesting performance difference.  Chris will look at whether there was a good reason to use the while loop.\n\n","2012-03-29T11:40:30.000+00:00","2012-06-29T16:34:54.000+00:00",394418,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,b8-41KDuKr344jeJe5cbLA",null,0.0,0,683.0,0,1,3325193,1,0.0,0.0,0.0,0.0,null,null]
