tickets, [52864503,905,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","dgRDGuZ4ar478MacwqEsg8","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Modify session validity check on upload to allow for very long uploads",3,"Currently FileSender checks for each chunk whether the user has a login session at the IdP.  This is unfortunate as the IdP controls when that session times out.  Experience from the Norwegian install show that uploads lasting longer than 8 hours suffer from session timeout at the IdP: the Norwegian identity federation IdP has a timeout after 8 hours.\n\nThere are several factors in SimpleSAMLphp that the SP controls but one it doesn't:  SessionNotOnOrAfter is sent in the SAML response from IdP to SP.  Olav Morken writes:\n\n\" It is also sent from the IdP to the SP, in the\n      \"SessionNotOnOrAfter\" attribute. The SP is supposed to use this\n      to determine when the session expires. In practice, this means\n      that the IdP can force the SP to reauthenticate more often than\n      whatever the SP has set in 'session.duration'. \"\n\nhttps://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/simplesamlphp/ERlbkoFpntw\n\nIt's the SessionNotOnOrAfter that bites us.  The implication is that when a FileSender upload lasts longer than SessionNotOnOrAfter ( 8 hours in Norway) the user gets a \"you're no longer authenticated\" message.  \n\nA solution is to change how FileSender deals with this: define a FileSender valid upload session, that remains valid for as long as an upload runs.  Only *after* the upload is completed will the IdP be asked again whether the user still has a valid session.  This means an upload will complete and should the user want to upload another file, a new session needs to be established if the old one has expired.\n\nA big advantage with pulling control over upload session validity into FileSender.  Xander reports this should not be too complicated.\n\nXander's list of points of consideration:\n- be aware of session hijacking etc.  The \"FileSender valid upload session\" should only be valid for a specific browser/client upload that started after normal authentication.  Probably a combination of sessionId and unique upload token (something we already have?)\n- such an upload token needs its own expiry, e.g. if 15 minutes without a new chunk then lose validity as AuthN token\n- what to do with the combination uploadcomplete and timedout SSP-session?  We need to present \"your upload has completed\" page.\n\nxander, please check the description and modify where needed.","2013-04-29T06:54:39.000+00:00","2016-02-25T09:06:12.000+00:00",6605143,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ,bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,dgRDGuZ4ar478MacwqEsg8","2015-03-27T16:56:05.000+00:00",0.0,0,-1.0,0,0,447388,0,1.0,3.0,0.0,0.0,"2015-03-27T16:56:05.000+00:00",null]
