tickets, [77279513,1073,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Minimise FileSender data privacy footprint",3,"With the Snowden revelations fresh in mind FileSender allows any person or organisation using it to subject its data to only the intelligence organisations of it's choosing.  Following well established engineering principles \"what isn't there can't be abused\" FileSender ought to be optimised to minimise the data privacy footprint of its users.  This also minimises possible exposure in case a FileSender instance should be compromised.  \n\nThis means logging least possible, by default deleting possibly sensitive logging in a timely fashion and in general ensure FileSender admins don't have (easy) access to privacy sensitive information.  It also means deleting privacy sensitive entries from the database, either by anonimising the privacy sensitive bits (like we did in the stats module) or by deleting them.\n\nIn particular we need to remove data that details communication meta-data: who sends what to whom.  It's probably OK to have such an overview on the institutional/domain level, but not on personal level.  When should it be purged?  After expire of the file/transaction or based on a time limit?  What about the audit trail?  Once purged, the audit trail disappears.  How does this work with the database being backup-ed?  What about sending the audit trail as an email to the sender?  What about making an \"incognito\" transaction? \n\nA number of FileSender features depend on having historical data available:\n-auto-complete in the To: field\n-the audit trail for a sender of a file, especially in the cases where the user chose to not receive emails of the file downloads\n-other?\n\nThe audit trail might be an important one, with anecdotal evidence and logging suggesting a number of users use FileSender in particular for the email receipts.  A straight forward solution is to simply gather the audit trail in an email and send it to the sender of the file on purge of the record.  That way the audit trail is where it belongs (transaction owner) and it's not with us.\n\nWe need to think this through carefully but do need to address it in our 2.0 release.  We also need to check up on the EU plans on the data privacy directive update that's underway now, it would be great to already be fully compliant :)\n\nComments are very much appreciated.","2014-02-03T19:39:17.000+00:00","2016-02-26T14:03:09.000+00:00",114623,null,"dPS9kyuyur3zYrab7jnrAJ","2016-02-26T14:03:09.000+00:00",0.0,0,-1.0,0,0,447388,0,3.0,3.0,0.0,0.0,"2016-02-26T14:03:09.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [77974513,1074,"d4oZSslSur3R7LeJe5aVNr","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Javascript errors when using IE ",3,"Reported by Lubos Kopecky.\n\nIE shows me error:\n\nWebpage error details\n\nUser Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1;\nTrident/4.0; SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR\n3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; .NET4.0C)\nTimestamp: Mon, 10 Feb 2014 21:23:12 UTC\n\nMessage: Object doesn't support this property or method\nLine: 649\nChar: 1\nCode: 0\n\nRelates to addEventListener not a function in IE - needs to detect if addEventListener is available or replace with attachEvent.This is an IE specific issue.\n\nCode below:\nwindow.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {(e.keyCode == 27 && \ne.preventDefault())})\n\nFix: Replace with.\nif (window.addEventListener){\n    window.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {(e.keyCode == 27 && \ne.preventDefault())})\n} else if (window.attachEvent){\nwindow.attachEvent('onkeydown', function(e) {(e.keyCode == 27 && \ne.preventDefault())})\n}\n ","2014-02-11T00:53:12.000+00:00","2014-03-23T21:35:27.000+00:00",3026383,null,",aNSALiyQSr3482eJe5cbCb,bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,0.0,0,-69.0,0,0,3325193,1,1.0,1.0,0.0,0.0,"2014-02-23T20:31:17.000+00:00",null]
