tickets, [92288623,1122,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb","b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Crypto: download of encrypted over2G-random.dat fails on qtest",1,"Observed on qtest with FF30.0 and Chrome on Mac OSX 10.8.5. Webconsole of chrome reports:\n\nUncaught ReferenceError: that is not defined downloader.js:50\nvalidateChunk downloader.js:50\ndecrypt downloader.js:61\nDownloader._requestComplete downloader.js:263\n(anonymous function)\n","2014-07-17T16:23:05.000+00:00","2014-12-10T15:55:31.000+00:00",1379273,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb,dno-zMULOr44oJacwqjQXA",null,0.0,0,-35.0,0,0,133342,1,1.0,1.0,0.0,0.0,"2014-07-17T20:25:20.000+00:00",null]
tickets, [92612223,1123,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,"b516sOlY8r3PPQeJe5afGb","Handling decomposed unicode in filenames",4,"On (at least) Mac OSX filenames with certain Unicode characters tend to be represented as 'decomposed unicode' (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode_equivalence for an explanation). Although FileSender transparantly handles those decomposed characters and leaves the actual handling to the browser and OS it looks like most notably Windows (when storing a file with 'decomposed unicode' characters from FireFox/Chrome) and IE11 (when displaying those files in My Files or a download page) doesn't handle those characters as expected.\n\nWe might consider 'fixing' this in FileSender by normalizing 'decomposed unicode' to 'precomposed unicode'. \n\nConsiderations:\n- The normalizer_normalize function of the PHP intl extension can be used for this, this requires PHP 5.3+ and adds extra dependencies (php5-intl, libicu)\n- Should we normalize when uploading (before storing the filename into the database) or only when displaying/downloading?\n","2014-07-22T14:47:25.000+00:00","2016-01-21T11:21:35.000+00:00",3026383,null,"bkpnJ4jEWr37jceJe5afGb",null,0.0,0,-84.0,0,0,3325193,1,1.0,2.0,0.0,0.0,"2015-11-17T13:54:22.000+00:00",null]
